<paragraph blockId="20.[167,775,345,741]" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,330,345,369]" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Identification.</emphasis>
This taxon is characterized by having an epiphytic-climbing habit, short stems and internodes, fibrous-persistent cataphylls, black glandular-punctate blades, usually pendent inflorescences, small spathes and spadices (&lt;1.0 cm long) and whitish berries. 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="20" pageNumber="671" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="scandens" subSpecies="pusillum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Anthurium scandens</emphasis>
subsp. 
<emphasis box="[409,502,514,538]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">pusillum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the typical subspecies (
<taxonomicName authority="subsp. scandens" box="[298,606,548,572]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="20" pageNumber="671" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="scandens" subSpecies="scandens">
<emphasis box="[298,428,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">A. scandens</emphasis>
subsp. 
<emphasis box="[508,606,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">scandens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) in having spadices with fewer flowers (&lt;13 flowers per spadix), small leaves, and very small spadices (up to 1.0 cm long). In the study area it could be confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Engl." authorityName="Engl." box="[582,771,649,673]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="20" pageNumber="671" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tonduzii">
<emphasis box="[582,703,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">A. tonduzii</emphasis>
Engl.
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter differs in having intact and deciduous cata- phylls, markedly ovate blades and reddish spadices.
</paragraph>
