<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="671" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[168,775,767,994]" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[168,457,767,791]" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[462,570,767,791]" name="Colombia" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[580,701,767,791]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry name="Ecuador" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[215,323,801,825]" name="Honduras" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Honduras</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[333,448,801,825]" name="Nicaragua" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Nicaragua</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[458,547,801,824]" name="Panama" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Panama</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[602,717,801,825]" name="Venezuela" pageId="20" pageNumber="671">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
. This taxon generally ocurrs in montane and submontane forests, above 
<quantity box="[294,363,868,892]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="671" unit="m" value="600.0">600 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Croat TB" box="[377,513,868,892]" pageId="20" pageNumber="671" refId="ref39425" refString="Croat TB (1986 b) A revision of genus Anthurium (Araceae) of Mexico and Central America. Part II: Panama. Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St Louis, 204 pp." type="book" year="1986">Croat 1986b</bibRefCitation>
). On Cerro Pirre, it represents a relatively rare species. Along the elevation gradient, it can only be observed in the montane cloud forest above 
<quantity box="[305,386,970,994]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="20" pageNumber="671" unit="m" value="1100.0">1100 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
